eriorly in the pudendal canal","Provides motor innervation to the internal urethral sphincter"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003ES2-S4 nerve roots\u003C/strong\u003E combine to form the pudendal nerve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe nerve exits the pelvis through the greater sciatic foramen (not the \u003Cstrong\u003Elesser sciatic foramen\u003C/strong\u003E) and travels around the sacrospinous ligament. After a short course in the gluteal region, it enters the perineum through the lesser sciatic foramen. The nerve continues to\u00a0course through\u00a0the pudendal (Alcock\u0027s) canal where it travels in an anterior direction (not \u003Cstrong\u003Eposteriorly\u003C/strong\u003E).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pudendal nerve provides motor innervation to the external anal sphincter, external urethral sphincter (not the \u003Cstrong\u003Einternal urethral sphincter\u003C/strong\u003E which receives autonomic innervation), and pelvic floor muscles. It also provides sensory innervation to the perineum and external genitalia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The pudendal nerve arises from sacral nerve roots S2-S4 and exits the pelvis through the greater sciatic foramen","The pudendal nerve travels anteriorly in the pudendal canal (Alcock\u0027s canal)"],"references":["Possover M, Forman A. Voiding Dysfunction Associated with Pudendal Nerve Entrapment. Curr Bladder Dysfunct Rep. 2012 Dec;7(4):281-285. doi: 10.1007/s11884-012-0156-5. Epub 2012 Sep 28. PMID: 23162676; PMCID: PMC3497942.","Beerten SG, Calabr\u00f2 RS. Pudendal Neuralgia: The Need for a Holistic Approach-Lessons From a Case Report. Innov Clin Neurosci. 2021 Apr-Jun;18(4-6):8-10. PMID: 34980976; PMCID: PMC8667704.","Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press","Bolla SR, Hoare BS, Varacallo M. Anatomy, 